 Appendix A Commands .book .book-body .page-wrapper .page-inner { max-width: 85%; } This appendix provides the formal definitions of all TUFLOW FV commands referenced in the model construction chapters. Each command definition describes its purpose, syntax, and allowable usage and is the reference for command specification. Where commands require input parameters, these are defined in the parameter appendix and should be consulted alongside this appendix. Where applicable, links are provided to the relevant processes appendices, which describe the governing equations and numerical formulation associated with command behaviour. The model construction chapters reference this appendix for formal command definitions and provide example syntax in context. Readers are expected to move between the model construction chapters, this appendix, and the parameter and processes appendices as needed. Instructions for using the interactive tables deployed in this appendix are provided in the manual introduction. All TUFLOW FV commands and descriptions are listed in Table A.1. A.0.1 Command syntax TUFLOW FV commands are displayed using coloured formatting, for example Catchment Pollutant Export Model ==. These commands can be copied directly into a control file, with arguments added as required. A.0.2 Argument syntax Arguments expected by TUFLOW FV commands (that is, information provided after ==) are displayed using contrasting colouring and are enclosed in angle brackets, for example \(\langle\)argument\(angle\). Argument definitions take one of the following forms: Single keyword options. Options are separated by semicolons. Options need to be used exactly as written because they are keywords. For example, \(\langle\)Washoff1;Shear1\(angle\) describes the available pollutant export models for the command Method ==. An example of implementing this description would therefore be Method == Washoff1 or for the Material == command, the argument is described as \(\langle\)All;Up to 10 comma separated material numbers\(angle\). An example of implementing this description would therefore be either Material == All or Material == 1, 6, 3\(d\) describes the single numeric value for the command Depth Threshold ==. These arguments are hyperlinked to other relevant information in this manual. An example of implementing this description would therefore be Recommendations. This is denoted with a rec: prefix \(\langle\)rec: plain text\(angle\) that recommends a command argument, such as a file path A.0.3 Commands All TUFLOW FV commands and descriptions are listed below. This page is intentionally wider than the main document to accommodate the level of detail provided in the command table. Additional tips for interacting with the table include: Commands are coloured. Although they appear underlined on mouse hover, they are not hyperlinks. Corresponding arguments are coloured and listed in the required order within angle brackets following each command. Each argument symbol is a hyperlink to its definition in the parameter appendix, where applicable. Parameter definitions include links to the relevant Science sections in the processes appendices. The final line of each command description links back to the relevant model construction section, where the command syntax is shown in context. Table A.1: TUFLOW FV Commands Command Description Atmospheric Stability Model == \(\langle\)\(M_{asm}\)\(angle\) Test Optional Atmospheric Update dt  == \(\langle\)\(dt_{atm}\)\(angle\) NA BC == \(\langle\)\(M_{bc}\)\(angle\) NA BC Default == \(\langle\)\(V_{bc-default}\)\(angle\) NA BC Default Update dt  == \(\langle\)\(dt_{bc-default}\)\(angle\) NA BC Event Source == \(\langle\)\(S_{bc-wildcard}\);\(S_{bc-eventsource}\)\(angle\) NA BC Header == \(\langle\)\(S_{bc-header}\)\(angle\) NA BC Nodestrings  == \(\langle\)\(S_{bc-nodestrings}\)\(angle\) NA BC Offset == \(\langle\)\(V_{bc-offset}\)\(angle\) NA BC Reference Time == \(\langle\)\(T_{bc-ref}\)\(angle\) N